    "analysis": "We relaxed fault filters and found short but meaningful segments (length=2, severity>=1.2). Top relaxed candidates include infrastructure components in the allowed root-cause set (IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis02, Redis01, Tomcat02) plus several ServiceTest entries (not in allowed list). Per-component counts show IG02 (3 segments), Redis02 (2), Mysql01 (2), others with 1–2 segments. Logs and error_logs remain empty so we must use traces to disambiguate among multiple candidate service/node-level faults. The next step is to (A) narrow relaxed segments to only allowed root-cause components and report earliest occurrence times per component, and (B) compute global thresholds for trace features (per trace_name and cmdb_id) using the full trace series, then detect trace anomalies in the incident window (1614857400–1614859200) where trace metric >= its global P95. This will tell us whether traces (e.g., IG01/IG02 → Tomcat*) show latency spikes coinciding with candidate metric anomalies and help identify the most downstream faulty service.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) From relaxed_fault_segments, filter to components that are in the allowed root-cause set: [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. Produce a compact table (max 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, relaxed_segment_count (number of relaxed segments for that component), earliest_segment_start_ts (minimum start_ts among its relaxed segments), top_kpis (up to 3 distinct kpi_name examples). Sort by relaxed_segment_count desc then earliest_segment_start_ts asc.\n2) Using trace.csv, compute global_P95 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) across the full available trace series (do NOT pre-filter). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window timestamps between 1614857400 and 1614859200 inclusive, and detect anomaly points where value >= global_P95. Aggregate these trace anomalies per (cmdb_id, trace_name) and return a compact summary (max 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value, global_P95. Sort by anomaly_count desc then max_value/global_P95 desc.\nStore full intermediate tables in kernel variables (filtered candidate list and trace anomaly points) but only print the compact summary tables described above."
}

{
    "analysis": "We relaxed anomaly filters and identified short (length=2) metric fault segments across several allowed components. IG02 has the most relaxed segments (3) and is a prime candidate; Redis02 and Mysql01 also show multiple segments. Trace anomaly aggregation shows several high-severity duration spikes on traces involving MG01, MG02, dockerA1/dockerA2 and strong duration ratio outliers (e.g., MG01 trace.from_dockerA1.duration_p95 ratio ≈16, MG02 trace.from_dockerA2.duration_mean ratio ≈9.9). Logs/error_logs are empty so we must rely on metric–trace correlation. To localize the two distinct failures, we need to correlate each candidate component’s metric fault segments (earliest occurrence) with overlapping/high-severity trace anomalies touching the same component (as source/target or in trace_name). This will reveal which faulty component is most downstream in traces and which metric fault aligns with large trace latency spikes—likely the root causes and their occurrence times. No final root-cause declarations yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For each allowed root-cause component present in filtered_relaxed_candidates (use that kernel var), find trace anomalies that involve that component. Specifically:\n1) For each component in filtered_relaxed_candidates, output: cmdb_id, relaxed_segment_count, earliest_segment_start_ts.\n2) For matching trace anomalies, include up to top 5 trace_anomaly_summary rows (by severity_ratio desc) where either (a) trace_anomaly_summary.cmdb_id == component OR (b) trace_anomaly_summary.trace_name contains the component name string. For each matched trace include: trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value, global_P95, severity_ratio.\n3) Return a compact table limited to 20 component rows; for each component include its matched traces as a nested list or as repeated rows (but total rows <= 20). Store the full result in kernel variable component_trace_correlation and return the compact display only.\nThis will let us see which components’ metric faults temporally overlap with high-severity trace spikes to identify the two failures' root causes and occurrence times."
}

{
    "analysis": "We filtered relaxed metric fault segments to the allowed root-cause components and correlated them with trace anomalies. MG02 and IG02 emerged as the strongest candidates: MG02 shows very large trace severity ratios (up to ~9.9) on traces to/from dockerA2 and MG02 (duration_mean/p95 spikes) in the 1614857820–1614858900 window; IG02 shows multiple metric segments and trace duration spikes involving Tomcat03 and self-duration around 1614857400–1614858660. Other components (Redis02, Mysql01, etc.) have metric-only short spikes with no matching trace anomalies, making them less likely root causes. Logs are empty, so we must rely on metric+trace temporal overlap to identify the most likely root cause components and the exact occurrence timestamps. To conclude the two failures, we need the earliest overlapping time where a component’s metric fault segment coincides with a high-severity trace anomaly for that same component (or where that component is the downstream faulty service in the trace). No final root-cause determination yet because we must confirm the precise overlap times for MG02 and IG02 (or any other top candidate).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For components MG02 and IG02, find the earliest metric–trace overlap and return compact results:\n1) From relaxed_fault_segments (kernel var), select all segments for MG02 and IG02 and list columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_type, start_ts, end_ts, length_minutes, severity. Limit to top 10 segments per component sorted by start_ts asc.\n2) From trace_anomaly_summary (kernel var), select all trace anomaly rows where (a) cmdb_id equals MG02 or IG02 OR (b) trace_name contains 'MG02' or 'IG02'. List columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value, global_P95, severity_ratio. Limit to top 20 rows sorted by severity_ratio desc.\n3) For each metric segment (from step 1), find trace anomaly rows (from step 2) that temporally overlap the segment (overlap condition: trace.earliest_anomaly_ts <= segment.end_ts AND trace.latest_anomaly_ts >= segment.start_ts). For each component, return the earliest overlapping pair and compute the overlap_timestamp as max(segment.start_ts, trace.earliest_anomaly_ts). Output a compact table (one row per component) with: cmdb_id, chosen_kpi_name, segment_start_ts, segment_end_ts, segment_severity, matched_trace_name, trace_earliest_anomaly_ts, trace_latest_anomaly_ts, trace_severity_ratio, overlap_timestamp.\nStore the full matching pairs table in kernel var component_overlap_matches but only print the compact outputs described above (max 20 rows total)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the workflow: computed global thresholds, detected anomalies in metric series, converted anomaly points into segments, relaxed filters to surface short/mid severity segments, and correlated metric segments with trace anomalies. Key findings so far: MG02 and IG02 are the strongest candidates. MG02 shows an earliest metric segment starting at 1614857400 (19:30:00+08) and very large trace-duration spikes in the broader window ~1614857820–1614858900 (severity ratios up to ~9.9). IG02 shows multiple metric segments with an earliest segment at 1614857880 (19:38:00+08) and moderate-to-high trace spikes involving Tomcat03 and IG02 self-duration in nearby windows (~1614857580–1614858660). Logs are empty, so we must rely on metric+trace temporal correlation. The last verification step retrieved the metric rows at the earliest segment starts for MG02 and IG02 but did not extract the concrete overlapping trace rows at those exact seconds; instead we have broader trace windows that overlap the segments. To finalize the two failures, we need a compact, concrete evidence table showing (for each candidate) the exact earliest metric anomaly row plus the overlapping trace anomaly rows (both the earliest overlapping trace and any later very-high-severity trace windows). This will allow a final, defensible declaration of root-cause component, exact occurrence datetime (first point of the matched fault segment), and the reason summarized from KPI names and trace impact.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Produce a compact evidence summary for MG02 and IG02 (limit returned rows to 10):\n1) For each component (MG02 and IG02) get the earliest relaxed segment start_ts from relaxed_fault_segments.\n2) Extract the metric row(s) from metric_window where cmdb_id equals the component and timestamp equals that earliest start_ts. Return columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, timestamp, value, global_P95, global_P05, and segment_severity.\n3) From trace_anomaly_summary, extract all trace rows that overlap the component's relaxed segment time OR fall inside the broader windows of interest: for MG02 use traces overlapping 1614857400..1614858900; for IG02 use traces overlapping 1614857400..1614859140 (the full IG02 trace coverage). Return columns: trace_cmdb_id (trace row owner), trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value, global_P95, severity_ratio. Sort MG02 traces by severity_ratio desc, IG02 traces by severity_ratio desc.\n4) For each component, present (a) the metric row(s) (step 2) and (b) the top 5 matching trace rows (step 3). Store results in kernel variable final_evidence and return only the compact table(s). Do not print full raw time series. "
}

